# Traffic Shaping
Empower the service owners to mark traffic as anomalous and allow the edge teams to handle the anomalous traffic before it comes to our backends

Key stakeholders
- monolith service use case (service teams): monolith platform would likely build this
- go service implementation:
    - e.g. configsd may be able to signal as well.
    - e.g. reposd can signal as well but receives

Marketing
- core savings
    - max conn in last week's incident was not good enough example
    - accounting: scraped all the time. we can see the traffic per route increase and get a core count for just scraper traffic. This core count goes to the edge.
    - simpler
- accuracy
    - the platform teams understand the limitations of their systems and know what traffic is unwanted / anomalous. they can flag this traffic and traffic teams can then make decisions on how best to limit that traffic in load balancers. This means that the platform teams are empowered to provide accurate signal to the load balancers who can then limit. The current state is that the platform owners attempt to use the tools the load balancers have at their disposal which are not as granular as required

